---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Aping — Andrew Shiau"
  description="An agent skill that writes documents in the Swiss style, and where I drew the line."
>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="back"><a href="/">← Index</a></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-10"><div class="shrule"></div><h1>Aping</h1></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <p class="dek c1-8" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
      An agent skill that writes HTML in the Swiss style — Müller-Brockmann's grid.
      You invoke it; the agent sets your content by that system's rules instead of
      the flat default a machine reaches for.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- The tension, and the line I drew. Dry. -->
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-8" style="margin-top:calc(var(--unit)*1.5)">
      <p>
        Aping means imitating. It's the honest word for what this does: I taught an
        agent to work in a style I admire, and it does the job well.
      </p>
      <p>
        I started a second skill aimed at a studio that's still working today, and
        stopped. Imitating a movement whose author died in 1996 is one thing; pointing
        a machine at a living studio's look and shipping the output is a different
        thing, and I didn't like it once I said it plainly. So the rule is: the dead,
        or a movement — not someone I could have just asked.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- meta callout: this site IS an output -->
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="block c1-6">
      <span class="st">This site is set in the /swiss style.</span>
      <span class="sd">Press g to see the grid under it.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h2>The style</h2></div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
    <div class="step accent" style="grid-column:span 8">
      <span class="sl">after Josef Müller-Brockmann (1914–1996)</span>
      <span class="st">/swiss</span>
      <span class="sd">A visible modular grid carrying large, precisely-set type. Structure from column alignment and thin rules, not boxes. One signal-red accent. This site is set in it.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Essays -->
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="c1-2"></div>
    <div class="c3-12"><h2>Written with it</h2></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid" style="margin-top:var(--unit)">
    <div class="links">
      <a href="/writing/10x-is-a-loop/">
        10x is a loop, not a prompt <span class="arrowc">→</span>
        <span class="lu">on AI-assisted engineering, evidence first</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/writing/canele/">
        What makes a canelé custardy <span class="arrowc">→</span>
        <span class="lu">one ratio, from six recipes</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="rule"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="facts">
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Form</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          The style is one <b>SKILL.md</b> — design tokens, a grid, and a
          MUST/MUST&nbsp;NOT checklist the agent follows. Output is a single
          self-contained HTML file.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="frow">
        <div class="fm">Source</div>
        <div class="ftx">
          Private repo. The pages here are the output; ask if you want the rules.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
